# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: messenger-rna
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The relative positions of structures along strands of nucleic acid, including genes and various protein binding sites, are usually noted as being either *upstream* (towards the 5′-end) or *downstream* (towards the 3′-end).
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] Directionality is related to, but different from, sense.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] Transcription of single-stranded RNA from a double-stranded DNA template requires the selection of one strand of the DNA template as the template strand that directly interacts with the nascent RNA due to complementary sequence.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The other strand is not copied directly, but necessarily its sequence will be similar to that of the RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] Transcription initiation sites generally occur on both strands of an organism's DNA, and specify the location, direction, and circumstances under which transcription will occur.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] If the transcript encodes one or (rarely) more proteins, translation of each protein by the ribosome will proceed in a 5′-to-3′ direction, and will extend the protein from its N-terminus toward its C-terminus.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] For example, in a typical gene a start codon (5′-ATG-3′) is a DNA sequence within the sense strand.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] Transcription begins at an upstream site (relative to the sense strand), and as it proceeds through the region it copies the 3′-TAC-5′ from the template strand to produce 5′-AUG-3′ within a messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The mRNA is scanned by the ribosome from the 5′ end, where the start codon directs the incorporation of a methionine (bacteria, mitochondria, and plastids use *N*-formylmethionine instead) at the N terminus of the protein.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] By convention, single strands of DNA and RNA sequences are written in a 5′-to-3′ direction except as needed to illustrate the pattern of base pairing.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 5′-end (pronounced "five prime end") designates the end of the DNA or RNA strand that has the fifth carbon in the sugar-ring of the deoxyribose or ribose at its terminus.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] A phosphate group attached to the 5′-end permits ligation of two nucleotides, i.e., the covalent binding of a 5′-phosphate to the 3′-hydroxyl group of another nucleotide, to form a phosphodiester bond.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] Removal of the 5′-phosphate prevents ligation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] To prevent unwanted nucleic acid ligation (e.g. self-ligation of a plasmid vector in DNA cloning), molecular biologists commonly remove the 5′-phosphate with a phosphatase.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 5′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site at which post-transcriptional capping occurs, a process which is vital to producing mature messenger RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] Capping increases the stability of the messenger RNA while it undergoes translation, providing resistance to the degradative effects of exonucleases.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] It consists of a methylated nucleotide (methylguanosine) attached to the messenger RNA in a rare 5′- to 5′-triphosphate linkage.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 5′-*flanking* region of a gene often denotes a region of DNA which is not transcribed into RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 5′-flanking region contains the gene promoter, and may also contain enhancers or other protein binding sites.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 5′-*untranslated* region (5′-UTR) is a region of a gene which is transcribed into mRNA, and is located at the 5′-end of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] This region of an mRNA may or may not be translated, but is usually involved in the regulation of translation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 5′-untranslated region is the portion of the DNA starting from the cap site and extending to the base just before the AUG translation initiation codon of the main coding sequence.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] This region may have sequences, such as the ribosome binding site and Kozak sequence, which determine the translation efficiency of the mRNA, or which may affect the stability of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 3′-end (three prime end) of a strand is so named due to it terminating at the hydroxyl group of the third carbon in the sugar-ring, and is known as the *tail end*.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 3′-hydroxyl is necessary in the synthesis of new nucleic acid molecules as it is ligated (joined) to the 5′-phosphate of a separate nucleotide, allowing the formation of strands of linked nucleotides.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] Molecular biologists can use nucleotides that lack a 3′-hydroxyl (dideoxyribonucleotides) to interrupt the replication of DNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] This technique is known as the dideoxy chain-termination method or the Sanger method, and is used to determine the order of nucleotides in DNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 3′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site of post-transcriptional polyadenylation, which attaches a chain of 50 to 250 adenosine residues to produce mature messenger RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] This chain helps in determining how long the messenger RNA lasts in the cell, influencing how much protein is produced from it.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 3′-*flanking* region is a region of DNA that is not copied into the mature mRNA, but which is present adjacent to 3′-end of the gene.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] It was originally thought that the 3′-flanking DNA was not transcribed at all, but it was discovered to be transcribed into RNA and quickly removed during processing of the primary transcript to form the mature mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 3′-flanking region often contains sequences that affect the formation of the 3′-end of the message.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] It may also contain enhancers or other sites to which proteins may bind.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 3′-*untranslated* region (3′-UTR) is a region of the DNA which *is* transcribed into mRNA and becomes the 3′-end of the message, but which does not contain protein coding sequence.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] Everything between the stop codon and the polyA tail is considered to be 3′-untranslated.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] The 3′-untranslated region may affect the translation efficiency of the mRNA or the stability of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-end] It also has sequences which are required for the addition of the poly(A) tail to the message, including the hexanucleotide AAUAAA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] In molecular genetics, the **three prime untranslated region** (**3′ UTR**) is the section of messenger RNA (mRNA) that immediately follows the translation termination codon.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The 3′ UTR often contains regulatory regions that post-transcriptionally influence gene expression.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] During gene expression, an mRNA molecule is transcribed from the DNA sequence and is later translated into a protein.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Several regions of the mRNA molecule are not translated into a protein including the 5′ cap, 5′ untranslated region, 3′ untranslated region and poly(A) tail.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Regulatory regions within the 3′ untranslated region can influence polyadenylation, translation efficiency, localization, and stability of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The 3′ UTR contains binding sites for both regulatory proteins and microRNAs (miRNAs).
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] By binding to specific sites within the 3′ UTR, miRNAs can decrease gene expression of various mRNAs by either inhibiting translation or directly causing degradation of the transcript.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The 3′ UTR also has silencer regions which bind to repressor proteins and will inhibit the expression of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Many 3′ UTRs also contain AU-rich elements (AREs).
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Proteins bind AREs to affect the stability or decay rate of transcripts in a localized manner or affect translation initiation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Furthermore, the 3′ UTR contains the sequence AAUAAA that directs addition of several hundred adenine residues called the poly(A) tail to the end of the mRNA transcript.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Poly(A) binding protein (PABP) binds to this tail, contributing to regulation of mRNA translation, stability, and export.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] For example, poly(A) tail bound PABP interacts with proteins associated with the 5′ end of the transcript, causing a circularization of the mRNA that promotes translation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The 3′ UTR can also contain sequences that attract proteins to associate the mRNA with the cytoskeleton, transport it to or from the cell nucleus, or perform other types of localization.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] In addition to sequences within the 3′ UTR, the physical characteristics of the region, including its length and secondary structure, contribute to translation regulation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] These diverse mechanisms of gene regulation ensure that the correct genes are expressed in the correct cells at the appropriate times.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The 3′ UTR of mRNA has a great variety of regulatory functions that are controlled by the physical characteristics of the region.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] One such characteristic is the length of the 3′ UTR, which in the mammalian genome has considerable variation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] This region of the mRNA transcript can range from 60 nucleotides to about 4000.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] On average the length for the 3′ UTR in humans is approximately 800 nucleotides, while the average length of 5′ UTRs is only about 200 nucleotides.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The length of the 3′ UTR is significant since longer 3′ UTRs are associated with lower levels of gene expression.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] One possible explanation for this phenomenon is that longer regions have a higher probability of possessing more miRNA binding sites that have the ability to inhibit translation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] In addition to length, the nucleotide composition also differs significantly between the 5′ and the 3′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The mean G+C percentage of the 5′ UTR in warm-blooded vertebrates is about 60% as compared to only 45% for 3′ UTRs.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] This is important because an inverse correlation has been observed between the G+C% of 5′ and 3′ UTRs and their corresponding lengths.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The UTRs that are GC-poor tend to be longer than those located in GC-rich genomic regions.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Sequences within the 3′ UTR also have the ability to degrade or stabilize the mRNA transcript.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Modifications that control a transcript's stability allow expression of a gene to be rapidly controlled without altering translation rates.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] One group of elements in the 3′ UTR that can help destabilize an mRNA transcript are the AU-rich elements (AREs).
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] These elements range in size from 50 to 150 base pairs and generally contain multiple copies of the pentanucleotide AUUUA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Early studies indicated that AREs can vary in sequence and fall into three main classes that differ in the number and arrangement of motifs.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Another set of elements that is present in both the 5′ and the 3′ UTR are iron response elements (IREs).
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The IRE is a stem-loop structure within the untranslated regions of mRNAs that encode proteins involved in cellular iron metabolism.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The mRNA transcript containing this element is either degraded or stabilized depending upon the binding of specific proteins and the intracellular iron concentrations.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The 3′ UTR also contains sequences that signal additions to be made, either to the transcript itself or to the product of translation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] For example, there are two different polyadenylation signals present within the 3′ UTR that signal the addition of the poly(A) tail.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] These signals initiate the synthesis of the poly(A) tail at a defined length of about 250 base pairs.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The primary signal used is the nuclear polyadenylation signal (PAS) with the sequence AAUAAA located toward the end of the 3′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] However, during early development cytoplasmic polyadenylation can occur instead and regulate the translational activation of maternal mRNAs.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The element that controls this process is called the CPE which is AU-rich and located in the 3′ UTR as well.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The CPE generally has the structure UUUUUUAU and is usually within 100 base pairs of the nuclear PAS.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Another specific addition signaled by the 3′ UTR is the incorporation of selenocysteine at UGA codons of mRNAs encoding selenoproteins.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Normally the UGA codon encodes for a stop of translation, but in this case a conserved stem-loop structure called the selenocysteine insertion sequence (SECIS) causes for the insertion of selenocysteine instead.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The 3′ untranslated region plays a crucial role in gene expression by influencing the localization, stability, export, and translation efficiency of an mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] It contains various sequences that are involved in gene expression, including microRNA response elements (MREs), AU-rich elements (AREs), and the poly(A) tail.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] In addition, the structural characteristics of the 3′ UTR as well as its use of alternative polyadenylation play a role in gene expression.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The 3′ UTR often contains microRNA response elements (MREs), which are sequences to which miRNAs bind. miRNAs are short, non-coding RNA molecules capable of binding to mRNA transcripts and regulating their expression.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] One miRNA mechanism involves partial base pairing of the 5′ seed sequence of an miRNA to an MRE within the 3′ UTR of an mRNA; this binding then causes translational repression.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] In addition to containing MREs, the 3′ UTR also often contains AU-rich elements (AREs), which are 50 to 150 bp in length and usually include many copies of the sequence AUUUA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] ARE binding proteins (ARE-BPs) bind to AU-rich elements in a manner that is dependent upon tissue type, cell type, timing, cellular localization, and environment.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] In response to different intracellular and extracellular signals, ARE-BPs can promote mRNA decay, affect mRNA stability, or activate translation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] This mechanism of gene regulation is involved in cell growth, cellular differentiation, and adaptation to external stimuli.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] It therefore acts on transcripts encoding cytokines, growth factors, tumor suppressors, proto-oncogenes, cyclins, enzymes, transcription factors, receptors, and membrane proteins.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The poly(A) tail contains binding sites for poly(A) binding proteins (PABPs).
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] These proteins cooperate with other factors to affect the export, stability, decay, and translation of an mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] PABPs bound to the poly(A) tail may also interact with proteins, such as translation initiation factors, that are bound to the 5′ cap of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] This interaction causes circularization of the transcript, which subsequently promotes translation initiation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Furthermore, it allows for efficient translation by causing recycling of ribosomes.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] While the presence of a poly(A) tail usually aids in triggering translation, the absence or removal of one often leads to exonuclease-mediated degradation of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Polyadenylation itself is regulated by sequences within the 3′ UTR of the transcript.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] These sequences include cytoplasmic polyadenylation elements (CPEs), which are uridine-rich sequences that contribute to both polyadenylation activation and repression.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] CPE-binding protein (CPEB) binds to CPEs in conjunction with a variety of other proteins in order to elicit different responses.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] While the sequence that constitutes the 3′ UTR contributes greatly to gene expression, the structural characteristics of the 3′ UTR also play a large role.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] In general, longer 3′ UTRs correspond to lower expression rates since they often contain more miRNA and protein binding sites that are involved in inhibiting translation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Human transcripts possess 3′ UTRs that are on average twice as long as other mammalian 3′ UTRs.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] This trend reflects the high level of complexity involved in human gene regulation.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] In addition to length, the secondary structure of the 3′ untranslated region also has regulatory functions.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Protein factors can either aid or disrupt folding of the region into various secondary structures.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The most common structure is a stem-loop, which provides a scaffold for RNA binding proteins and non-coding RNAs that influence expression of the transcript.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Another mechanism involving the structure of the 3′ UTR is called alternative polyadenylation (APA), which results in mRNA isoforms that differ only in their 3′ UTRs.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] This mechanism is especially useful for complex organisms as it provides a means of expressing the same protein but in varying amounts and locations.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] It is utilized by about half of human genes.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] APA can result from the presence of multiple polyadenylation sites or mutually exclusive terminal exons.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Since it can affect the presence of protein and miRNA binding sites, APA can cause differential expression of mRNA transcripts by influencing their stability, export to the cytoplasm, and translation efficiency.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Scientists use a number of methods to study the complex structures and functions of the 3′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Even if a given 3′ UTR in an mRNA is shown to be present in a tissue, the effects of localization, functional half-life, translational efficiency, and trans-acting elements must be determined to understand the 3′ UTR's full functionality.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Computational approaches, primarily by sequence analysis, have shown the existence of AREs in approximately 5 to 8% of human 3′ UTRs and the presence of one or more miRNA targets in as many as 60% or more of human 3′ UTRs.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Software can rapidly compare millions of sequences at once to find similarities between various 3′ UTRs within the genome.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Experimental approaches have been used to define sequences that associate with specific RNA-binding proteins; specifically, recent improvements in sequencing and cross-linking techniques have enabled fine mapping of protein binding sites within the transcript.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Induced site-specific mutations, for example those that affect the termination codon, polyadenylation signal, or secondary structure of the 3′ UTR, can show how mutated regions can cause translation deregulation and disease.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] These types of transcript-wide methods should help our understanding of known cis elements and trans-regulatory factors within 3′ UTRs.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] 3′ UTR mutations can be very consequential because one alteration can be responsible for the altered expression of many genes.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Transcriptionally, a mutation may affect only the allele and genes that are physically linked.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] However, since 3′ UTR binding proteins also function in the processing and nuclear export of mRNA, a mutation can also affect other unrelated genes.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Dysregulation of ARE-binding proteins (AUBPs) due to mutations in AU-rich regions can lead to diseases including tumorigenesis (cancer), hematopoietic malignancies, leukemogenesis, and developmental delay/autism spectrum disorders.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] An expanded number of trinucleotide (CTG) repeats in the 3′ UTR of the dystrophia myotonica protein kinase (DMPK) gene causes myotonic dystrophy.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Retro-transposal 3-kilobase insertion of tandem repeat sequences within the 3′ UTR of fukutin protein is linked to Fukuyama-type congenital muscular dystrophy.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Elements in the 3′ UTR have also been linked to human acute myeloid leukemia, alpha-thalassemia, neuroblastoma, Keratinopathy, Aniridia, IPEX syndrome, and congenital heart defects.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] The few UTR-mediated diseases identified only hint at the countless links yet to be discovered.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Despite current understanding of 3′ UTRs, they are still relative mysteries.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Since mRNAs usually contain several overlapping control elements, it is often difficult to specify the identity and function of each 3′ UTR element, let alone the regulatory factors that may bind at these sites.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Additionally, each 3′ UTR contains many alternative AU-rich elements and polyadenylation signals.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] These cis- and trans-acting elements, along with miRNAs, offer a virtually limitless range of control possibilities within a single mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/3-utr] Future research through the increased use of deep-sequencing based ribosome profiling will reveal more regulatory subtleties as well as new control elements and AUBPs.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] In molecular biology, the **five-prime cap** (**5′ cap**) is a specially altered nucleotide on the 5′ end of some primary transcripts such as precursor messenger RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] In eukaryotes, the main form is **mRNA capping**, a highly regulated process that uses 7-methylguanosine, vital in the creation of stable and mature messenger RNA able to undergo translation during protein synthesis.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Mitochondrial mRNA and chloroplastic mRNA are not capped.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] When an RNA is made by a RNA polymerase (RNAP), it has a triphosphate group on its 5' end due to the use of nucleoside triphosphates (NTP, pppN) by the RNAP.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] In eukaryotes, the exposed ppp end is "capped" by a guanine soon after it is freed from the RNAP, forming the 5' cap.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Due to how it formed, the cap connects to mRNA via an unusual 5′ to 5′ triphosphate linkage.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] This guanosine is methylated on the 7 position directly after capping *in vivo* by a methyltransferase.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The result is a 7-methylguanylate (m7G) cap.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Cap-0, mRNA with only the m7G cap, is the basic cap structure for eukaryotic mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Its structure is written as m7GpppN: m7G, connected to a string of three phosphate groups, then to any other nucleotide.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The first and second transcribed nucleotides can also be 2' O-methylated (N → Nm), leading to the Cap-1 and Cap-2 structures, respectively.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Cap-1 has a methylated 2′-hydroxy group on the first ribose sugar[m7G ppp Nm-], while cap-2 has methylated 2′-hydroxy groups on the first two ribose sugars [m7G ppp Nm p Nm-], shown on the right.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] This is more common in higher eukaryotes and thought to be part of the innate immune system to recognize mRNAs from other organisms.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The choice of whether to make these modifications vary by organism and the starting bases of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] This strategy is also adopted by some viruses that infect eukaryotes.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] In all organisms, mRNA molecules can be decapped in a process known as messenger RNA decapping.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] This is usually followed by degradation of the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The starting point for capping with 7-methylguanylate is the unaltered 5′ end of an RNA molecule, which terminates at a triphosphate group.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] This features a final nucleotide followed by three phosphate groups attached to the 5′ carbon.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The capping process is initiated before the completion of transcription, as the nascent pre-mRNA (ppp(-5′)N[pN]n) is being synthesized.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] GTP is added to the terminal bisphosphate by mRNA guanylyltransferase (GTase), losing a pyrophosphate from the GTP substrate in the process.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The above describes the canonical capping process involving a TPase, GTase, and a MTase, arriving at Cap-0.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Cap-1 and Cap-2 can be produced from Cap-0 with 2'-O-methylation by a mRNA (nucleoside-2'-O-)-methyltransferase (2'-O-MTase).
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Further modification is also possible: for example, if the nearest cap-adjacent nucleotide is 2′-*O*-ribose methyl-adenosine (i.e.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] (m7G)ppp(Am)[pN]n), it can be further methylated at the N6 methyl position to form *N*6-methyladenosine, resulting in 5′(m7G)ppp(N6Am)[pN]n.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] For capping with 7-methylguanylate, the capping enzyme complex (CEC) binds to RNA polymerase II before transcription starts.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] As soon as the 5′ end of the new transcript emerges from RNA polymerase II, the CEC carries out the capping process (this kind of mechanism ensures capping, as with polyadenylation).
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The enzymes for capping can only bind to RNA polymerase II, ensuring specificity to only these transcripts, which are almost entirely mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Promotion of 5′ proximal intron excision.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Nuclear export of RNA is regulated by the cap binding complex (CBC), which binds exclusively to 7-methylguanylate-capped RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The CBC is then recognized by the nuclear pore complex and exported.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Once in the cytoplasm after the pioneer round of translation, the CBC is replaced by the translation factors eIF4E and eIF4G of the eIF4F complex.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] This complex is then recognized by other translation initiation machinery including the ribosome.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Capping with 7-methylguanylate prevents 5′ degradation in multiple ways.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] First, degradation of the mRNA by 5′ exonucleases (which are abundant in the nucleus) is prevented by chemically looking like a 3′ end.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Second, the CBC and eIF4E/eIF4G block the access of decapping enzymes to the cap.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Additional cap-binding proteins also contribute.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] This increases the half-life of the mRNA, essential in eukaryotes as the export and translation processes take significant time.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The mechanism of 5′ proximal intron excision promotion is not well understood, but the 7-methylguanylate cap appears to loop around and interact with the spliceosome in the splicing process, promoting intron excision.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Decapping of a 7-methylguanylate-capped mRNA is catalyzed by the decapping complex made up of at least Dcp1 and Dcp2, which must compete with eIF4E to bind the cap.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Thus the 7-methylguanylate cap is a marker of an actively translating mRNA and is used by cells to regulate mRNA half-lives in response to new stimuli.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Undesirable mRNAs are sent to P-bodies for temporary storage or decapping, the details of which are still being resolved.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The corresponding enzyme activity is m7G(5')pppN diphosphatase, which produces the products m7Gp and ppN-RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Viruses that infect eukaryotes employ a variety of stretegies to form caps that the host would recognize.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Some encode the canonical trio of enzymes, occasionally in combination with a 2'-O-MTase (e.g. vaccinia virus).
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] There are also ones that use more different options.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] For example, picornavirus has its RdRP build RNAs starting with a protein, which acts as a cap.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] In addition, some of the Mimiviridae carry a variant of eIF4F for their own use.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The viral version specifically recognizes m7GpppAm-mRNA, the kind made by other viral proteins, and is not downregulated in times of stress like the host version.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Eukaryotic small nuclear RNAs contain unique 5′-caps.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Sm-class snRNAs are found with 2,2,7-trimethylguanosine (m3G) caps, while Lsm-class snRNAs are found with monomethyl caps.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Both are linked to the 5' end of the RNA via a triphosphate (ppp) linkage (in 5'-5' orientation in the case of m3G), like the mRNA cap.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] In bacteria, and potentially also in higher organisms, some RNAs are capped with NAD+, NADH, or 3′-dephospho-coenzyme A (dpCoA).
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Unlike the eukaryotic caps, the bacterial caps are linked to 5' end of the RNA using a regular monophosphate (p) linkage; they internally contain a diphosphate linkage, however.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] The mechanism of capping with NAD(+/H) or dpCoA is different.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Capping with these groups is accomplished through an "ab initio capping mechanism," in which NAD(+/H) or dpCoA serves as a "non-canonical initiating nucleotide" (NCIN) for transcription initiation by RNA polymerase and thereby directly is incorporated into the RNA product.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] This is due to their structual similarity with ATP.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Both bacterial RNA polymerase and eukaryotic RNA polymerase II are able to carry out this "ab initio capping mechanism" *in vitro*.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] Capping with NAD(+/H) or dpCoA is targeted by promoter sequence.
[src:messenger-rna/5-cap] NCIN capping occurs only at promoters that have certain sequences at and immediately upstream of the transcription start site and therefore occurs only for RNAs synthesized from certain promoters.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The **five prime untranslated region** **(5′ UTR)**, or **leader sequence**, **transcript leader**, or **leader RNA**, is the region of a messenger RNA (mRNA) that is directly upstream from the initiation codon.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This region is important for the regulation of translation of a transcript by differing mechanisms in viruses, prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Despite its name, the 5′ UTR, or a portion of it, is sometimes translated into a protein product.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This product may involve in regulation of transcription, and translation of the main coding sequence of the mRNA, such as the sex-lethal gene in *Drosophila*.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Regulatory elements within 5′ UTRs have also been linked to mRNA export.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] In many organisms, however, the 5′ UTR is completely untranslated, instead forming a complex secondary structure to regulate translation.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The 5′ UTR begins at the transcription start site and ends one nucleotide before the initiation sequence (usually AUG) of the coding region.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] In prokaryotes, the length of the 5′ UTR tends to be 3–10 nucleotides long, while in eukaryotes it tends to be anywhere from 100 to several thousand nucleotides long.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] For example, the *ste11* transcript in *Schizosaccharomyces pombe* has a 2273 nucleotide 5′ UTR while the *lac* operon in *Escherichia coli* only has seven nucleotides in its 5′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The differing sizes are likely due to the complexity of the eukaryotic regulation which the 5′ UTR holds as well as the larger pre-initiation complex that must form to begin translation.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The 5′ UTR can also be completely missing, in the case of **leaderless mRNAs**.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Ribosomes of all three domains of life accept and translate such mRNAs.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Such sequences are naturally found in all three domains of life.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Humans have many pressure-related genes under a 2–3 nucleotide leader.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Mammals also have other types of ultra-short leaders like the TISU sequence.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The elements of a eukaryotic and prokaryotic 5′ UTR differ greatly.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The prokaryotic 5′ UTR contains a ribosome binding site (RBS), also known as the Shine–Dalgarno sequence (AGGAGGU), which is usually 3–10 base pairs upstream from the initiation codon.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] In contrast, the eukaryotic 5′ UTR contains the Kozak consensus sequence (ACCAUGG), which contains the initiation codon.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The eukaryotic 5′ UTR also contains *cis*-acting regulatory elements called upstream open reading frames (uORFs) and upstream AUGs (uAUGs) and termination codons, which have a great impact on the regulation of translation (see below).
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Unlike prokaryotes, 5′ UTRs can harbor introns in eukaryotes.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] In humans, ~35% of all genes harbor introns within the 5′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] As the 5′ UTR has high GC content, secondary structures often occur within it.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Hairpin loops are one such secondary structure that can be located within the 5′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] These secondary structures also impact the regulation of translation.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] In bacteria, the initiation of translation occurs when IF-3, along with the 30S ribosomal subunit, bind to the Shine–Dalgarno (SD) sequence of the 5′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This then recruits many other proteins, such as the 50S ribosomal subunit, which allows for translation to begin.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Each of these steps regulates the initiation of translation.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Initiation in Archaea is less understood.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] SD sequences are much rarer, and the initiation factors have more in common with eukaryotic ones.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] In both domains, genes without Shine–Dalgarno sequences are also translated in a less understood manner.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] A requirement seems to be a lack of secondary structure near the initiation codon.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The regulation of translation in eukaryotes is more complex than in prokaryotes.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Initially, the eIF4F complex is recruited to the 5′ cap, which in turn recruits the ribosomal complex to the 5′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Both eIF4E and eIF4G bind the 5′ UTR, which limits the rate at which translational initiation can occur.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] However, this is not the only regulatory step of translation that involves the 5′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] RNA-binding proteins sometimes serve to prevent the pre-initiation complex from forming.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] An example is regulation of the *msl2* gene.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The protein SXL attaches to an intron segment located within the 5′ UTR segment of the primary transcript, which leads to the inclusion of the intron after processing.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This sequence allows the recruitment of proteins that bind simultaneously to both the 5′ and 3′ UTR, not allowing translation proteins to assemble.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] However, it has also been noted that SXL can also repress translation of RNAs that do not contain a poly(A) tail, or more generally, 3′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Another important regulator of translation is the interaction between 3′ UTR and the 5′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The closed-loop structure inhibits translation.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This has been observed in *Xenopus laevis*, in which eIF4E bound to the 5′ cap interacts with Maskin bound to CPEB on the 3′ UTR, creating translationally inactive transcripts.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This translational inhibition is lifted once CPEB is phosphorylated, displacing the Maskin binding site, allowing for the polymerization of the PolyA tail, which can recruit the translational machinery by means of PABP.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] However, this mechanism has been under great scrutiny.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Iron levels in cells are maintained by translation regulation of many proteins involved in iron storage and metabolism.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The 5′ UTR has the ability to form a hairpin loop secondary structure (known as the iron response element or IRE) that is recognized by iron-regulatory proteins (IRP1 and IRP2).
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] In low levels of iron, the ORF of the target mRNA is blocked as a result of steric hindrance from the binding of IRP1 and IRP2 to the IRE.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] When iron is high, then the two iron-regulatory proteins do not bind as strongly and allow proteins to be expressed that have a role in iron concentration control.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This function has gained some interest after it was revealed that the translation of amyloid precursor protein may be disrupted due to a single-nucleotide polymorphism to the IRE found in the 5′ UTR of its mRNA, leading to a spontaneous increased risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Another form of translational regulation in eukaryotes comes from unique elements on the 5′ UTR called upstream open reading frames (uORF).
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] These elements are fairly common, occurring in 35–49% of all human genes.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] A uORF is a coding sequence located in the 5′ UTR located upstream of the coding sequences initiation site.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] These uORFs contain their own initiation codon, known as an upstream AUG (uAUG).
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This codon can be scanned for by ribosomes and then translated to create a product, which can regulate the translation of the main protein coding sequence or other uORFs that may exist on the same transcript.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The translation of the protein within the main ORF after a uORF sequence has been translated is known as reinitiation.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The process of reinitiation is known to reduce the translation of the ORF protein.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Control of protein regulation is determined by the distance between the uORF and the first codon in the main ORF.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] A uORF has been found to increase reinitiation with the longer distance between its uAUG and the start codon of the main ORF, which indicates that the ribosome needs to reacquire translation factors before it can carry out translation of the main protein.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] For example, *ATF4* regulation is performed by two uORFs further upstream, named uORF1 and uORF2, which contain three amino acids and fifty-nine amino acids, respectively.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The location of uORF2 overlaps with the *ATF4* ORF.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] During normal conditions, the uORF1 is translated, and then translation of uORF2 occurs only after eIF2-TC has been reacquired.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Translation of the uORF2 requires that the ribosomes pass by the *ATF4* ORF, whose start codon is located within uORF2.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] However, during stress conditions, the 40S ribosome will bypass uORF2 because of a decrease in concentration of eIF2-TC, which means the ribosome does not acquire one in time to translate uORF2.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Viral (as well as some eukaryotic) 5′ UTRs contain internal ribosome entry sites, which is a cap-independent method of translational activation.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Instead of building up a complex at the 5′ cap, the IRES allows for direct binding of the ribosomal complexes to the transcript to begin translation.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] The IRES enables the viral transcript to translate more efficiently due to the lack of needing a preinitiation complex, allowing the virus to replicate quickly.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Transcription of the *msl-2* transcript is regulated by multiple binding sites for fly *Sxl* at the 5′ UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] In particular, these poly-uracil sites are located close to a small intron that is spliced in males, but kept in females through splicing inhibition.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] This splicing inhibition is maintained by *Sxl*.
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] When present, *Sxl* will repress the translation of *msl2* by increasing translation of a start codon located in a uORF in the 5′ UTR (see above for more information on uORFs).
[src:messenger-rna/5-utr] Also, *Sxl* outcompetes TIA-1 to a poly(U) region and prevents snRNP (a step in alternative splicing) recruitment to the 5′ splice site.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] After the discovery and publication by Shaw that AREs don't function at the DNA level but rather in mRNA, ribonucleotide sequences with frequent adenine and uridine bases in 3' UTR of an mRNA were eventually classified (see description below).
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] While AREs often target the mRNA for rapid degradation, ARE-directed mRNA degradation can be influenced by many exogenous factors that modulate a cell's function, including phorbol esters, calcium ionophores, cytokines, and transcription inhibitors.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] In 1989, Kruys and Shaw reported that AREs could also function to block the translation of mRNAs, using Xenopus oocytes as the translational assay system.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] This blockade could be explained by the binding of the ELAVL2 isoform that is found in oocytes to AREs.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Further research revealed that AREs could sometimes also function to increase translation of mRNAs by recruiting the microRNP-related proteins FXR1 and AGO2 during conditions of cell cycle arrest.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] In 2025 it was reported that a synthetic ARE, with a certain configuration of AUUUA repeats that enhance HuR binding, can increase protein expression up to 5-fold.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] This finding may be useful for many mRNA-based therapeutics.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Collectively, all of these observations suggest that receptor signaling and the local changing dynamic conditions within a cell (including starvation and stress) dictates how the ARE of an mRNA will function.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Each of these data observations strongly suggest that AREs play a critical role in the regulation of gene expression during cell growth and differentiation, as well as the immune response.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] As evidence of its critical role, deletion of the AREs from the 3' UTR in either the TNF gene or GM-CSF gene in mice leads to over expression of each respective gene product, causing dramatic disease phenotypes.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] In short, the AU-rich element illustrates how after genes are transcribed into mRNA, there is another level of control that can determine how much protein will be translated from an mRNA (posttransciptional gene regulation).
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] AREs have been divided into three classes with different sequences.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] The best characterized adenylate uridylate (AU)-rich Elements have a core sequence of AUUUA within U-rich sequences (for example WWWU(AUUUA)UUUW where W is A or U).
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] This lies within a 50–150 base sequence, repeats of the core AUUUA element are often required for function.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] A single AUUUA shows very little mRNA destabilizing function, whereas AUUUAUUUAUUUA shows some mRNA destabilizing function when inserted into the 3'UTR of a rabbit beta-globin gene.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] HuA, HuB, HuC, HuD, HuR) bind to these elements and stabilize the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] The sequence AUUUAUUUA is the minimal sequence required for HuR binding and multiple AUUUA sequences can be inserted at the beginning of the 3' UTR to maximize HuR binding.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] HuR contains three RNA recognition motifs (RRMs): Tandem RRM1 and 2, followed by a flexible linker and a C-terminal RRM3.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] The co-crystal structure of RRM3 provides structural and mechanistic insights into how RRM3 in HuR binds to various AU-rich sequences.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] The RNA binding protein RMB47 has been shown to bind to AREs in IL-10 mRNA and Ectodermal neural cortex 1 (ENC1) mRNA and stabilize those mRNAs.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Other ARE binding proteins (AUF1, TTP, BRF1, TIA-1, TIAR, and KSRP) destabilize the mRNA, miRNAs may also bind to some of them.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] For example, the human microRNA, miR16, contains an UAAAUAUU sequence that is complementary to the ARE sequence and appears to be required for ARE-mRNA turnover.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] HuD (also called ELAVL4) binds to AREs and increases the half-life of ARE-bearing mRNAs in neurons during brain development and plasticity.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] The RNA binding protein DDX21 has been reported to bind to AREs and confer mTOR-mediated translation control of cytokines during T cell activation.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] AREsite—a database for ARE containing genes—has recently been developed with the aim to provide detailed bioinformatic characterization of AU-rich elements.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] No real ARE consensus sequence has been determined yet, and these categories are based neither on the same biological functions, nor on the homologous proteins.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] AREs are recognized by RNA binding proteins such as tristetraprolin (TTP), AUF1, and Hu Antigen R (HuR).
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] RNA-binding proteins that bind AREs have been termed ARE-BPs and as of 2019, about 20 ARE-BPs have been identified.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Although the exact mechanism is not very well understood, recent publications have attempted to propose the action of some of these ARE-BPs.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] One characteristic of many ARE-BPs is that they can shuttle between the nucleus and cytoplasm and exert different functions to control gene expression based on their subcellular location.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] AUF1, also known as hnRNP D, binds AREs through RNA recognition motifs (RRMs).
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] AUF1 is also known to interact with the translation initiation factor eIF4G and with poly(A)-binding protein, indicating that AUF1 senses the translational status of mRNA and decays accordingly through the excision of the poly(A) tail.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] TTP's (ZFP36's) expression is rapidly induced by insulin.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Immunoprecipitation experiments have shown that TTP co-precipitates with an exosome, suggesting that it helps recruit exosomes to the mRNA containing AREs.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] TTP appears to promote the processive deadenylation activity of CCR4–NOT on mRNAs containing AREs, with phosphorylation-dependent interactions with cytoplasmic poly(A)-binding protein (PABPC1) potentially enhancing deadenylation and promoting regulated mRNA decay.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] TTP can also repress mRNA translation after binding to AREs by using 4EHP-GYF2 as a cofactor.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Alternatively, HuR proteins have a stabilizing effect—their binding to AREs increases the half-life of mRNAs.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Similar to other RNA-binding proteins, this class of proteins contain three RRMs, two of which are specific to ARE elements.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] A likely mechanism for HuR action relies on the idea that these proteins compete with other proteins that normally have a destabilizing effect on mRNAs.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] HuRs are involved in genotoxic response—they accumulate in the cytoplasm in response to UV exposure and stabilize mRNAs that encode proteins involved in DNA repair.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Problems with mRNA stability have been identified in viral genomes, cancer cells, and various diseases.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Research shows that many of these problems arise because of faulty ARE function.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Deficiency of the ZFP36 family show that ZFP36 ARE binding proteins are critical regulators of T cell homeostasis and autoimmunity.
[src:messenger-rna/au-rich-element] Deficient mice have also indicated a protective role for ZFP36 ARE binding proteins via regulating cytokine levels in the thymic microenvironment, thereby preventing thymic involution.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] mRNA is created during the process of transcription, where an enzyme (RNA polymerase) converts the gene into primary transcript mRNA (also known as pre-mRNA).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This pre-mRNA usually still contains introns, regions that will not go on to code for the final amino acid sequence.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] These are removed in the process of RNA splicing, leaving only exons, regions that will encode the protein.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This exon sequence constitutes mature mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Mature mRNA is then read by the ribosome, and the ribosome creates the protein utilizing amino acids carried by transfer RNA (tRNA).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] All of these processes form part of the central dogma of molecular biology, which describes the flow of genetic information in a biological system.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] As in DNA, genetic information in mRNA is contained in the sequence of nucleotides, which are arranged into codons consisting of three ribonucleotides each.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Each codon codes for a specific amino acid, except the stop codons, which terminate protein synthesis.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The translation of codons into amino acids requires two other types of RNA: transfer RNA, which recognizes the codon and provides the corresponding amino acid, and ribosomal RNA (rRNA), the central component of the ribosome's protein-manufacturing machinery.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The concept of mRNA was first conceived by Sydney Brenner and Francis Crick in 1960 during a conversation with François Jacob.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In May 1961, messenger RNA was experimentally characterized in two back-to-back *Nature* papers: one by Brenner, Jacob, and Meselson, and one by Gros and colleagues (including Watson).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] While analyzing the data in preparation for publication, Jacob and Jacques Monod coined the term "messenger RNA".
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The brief existence of an mRNA molecule begins with transcription, and ultimately ends in degradation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] During its life, an mRNA molecule may also be processed, edited, and transported prior to translation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Eukaryotic mRNA molecules often require extensive processing and transport, while prokaryotic mRNA molecules do not.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] A molecule of eukaryotic mRNA and the proteins surrounding it are together called a messenger RNP.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Transcription is the process by which genetic information stored in DNA is copied into RNA by the enzyme RNA polymerase.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] During transcription, RNA polymerase binds to a promoter sequence on the DNA and synthesizes a complementary RNA strand (mRNA) from the DNA template.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This process differs between prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In prokaryotes, transcription occurs in the cytoplasm.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Because prokaryotes lack a membrane-bound nucleus, ribosomes can attach to the nascent mRNA strand and begin translation while transcription is still in progress.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In eukaryotes, transcription occurs within the cell nucleus.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The initial product of transcription is not functional mRNA but is termed *precursor mRNA* or *pre-mRNA*.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This pre-mRNA must undergo extensive processing (including 5' capping, splicing to remove non-coding introns, and 3' polyadenylation) to become *mature mRNA*.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Once processed, the mature mRNA is exported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm for translation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Whereas DNA contains thymine (T), RNA contains uracil (U).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] During the process of transcription, the enzyme RNA polymerase incorporates uracil opposite adenine bases located on the DNA template strand.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Therefore, the resulting RNA transcript contains uracil in the positions where the coding DNA strand contains thymine.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Structurally, uracil–adenine (U–A) base pairs closely resemble thymine–adenine (T–A) base pairs, which ensures that the genetic information carried by the sequence is faithfully preserved.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] A frequently cited explanation for the presence of thymine in DNA involves the necessity of genome maintenance.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Because cytosine can spontaneously deaminate to form uracil, DNA repair systems recognize uracil as a form of damage.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The utilization of thymine as a standard base allows the cell to distinguish legitimate bases from errors, thereby maintaining uracil as a specific signal for repair.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Processing of mRNA differs greatly among eukaryotes, bacteria, and archaea.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Non-eukaryotic mRNA is, in essence, mature upon transcription and requires no processing, except in rare cases.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Eukaryotic pre-mRNA, however, requires several processing steps before its transport to the cytoplasm and its translation by the ribosome.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The extensive processing of eukaryotic pre-mRNA that leads to the mature mRNA is the RNA splicing, a mechanism by which introns or outrons (non-coding regions) are removed and exons (coding regions) are joined.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] A *5' cap* (also termed an RNA cap, an RNA 7-methylguanosine cap, or an RNA m7G cap) is a modified guanine nucleotide that has been added to the "front" or 5' end of a eukaryotic messenger RNA shortly after the start of transcription.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The 5' cap consists of a terminal 7-methylguanosine residue that is linked through a 5'-5'-triphosphate bond to the first transcribed nucleotide.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Its presence is critical for recognition by the ribosome and protection from RNases.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Cap addition is coupled to transcription, and occurs co-transcriptionally, such that each influences the other.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Shortly after the start of transcription, the 5' end of the mRNA being synthesized is bound by a cap-synthesizing complex associated with RNA polymerase.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This enzymatic complex catalyzes the chemical reactions that are required for mRNA capping.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Synthesis proceeds as a multi-step biochemical reaction.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In some instances, an mRNA molecule is edited, which changes the nucleotide composition of the transcript.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] A prominent example in humans involves the apolipoprotein B mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In certain tissues, RNA editing of this transcript creates a premature stop codon, which results in the production of a shorter protein variant.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Another well studied mechanism is A-to-I (adenosine-to-inosine) editing.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This reaction is catalyzed by ADAR enzymes (adenosine deaminase acting on RNA) and typically occurs within double-stranded RNA regions.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] A-to-I editing may occur in both coding sequences and untranslated regions.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Through these modifications, the process can affect protein recoding, RNA structure, and gene regulation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Polyadenylation is the covalent linkage of a polyadenylyl moiety to a messenger RNA molecule.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In eukaryotic organisms most messenger RNA (mRNA) molecules are polyadenylated at the 3' end, but recent studies have shown that short stretches of uridine (oligouridylation) are also common.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The poly(A) tail and the protein bound to it aid in protecting mRNA from degradation by exonucleases.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Polyadenylation is also important for transcription termination, export of the mRNA from the nucleus, and translation. mRNA can also be polyadenylated in prokaryotic organisms, where poly(A) tails act to facilitate, rather than impede, exonucleolytic degradation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Polyadenylation occurs during and/or immediately after transcription of DNA into RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] After transcription has been terminated, the mRNA chain is cleaved through the action of an endonuclease complex associated with RNA polymerase.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] After the mRNA has been cleaved, around 200–250 adenosine residues are added to the free 3' end at the cleavage site.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This reaction is catalyzed by polyadenylate polymerase.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Just as in alternative splicing, there can be more than one polyadenylation variant of an mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Polyadenylation site mutations can occur.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The primary RNA transcript of a gene is cleaved at the poly(A) addition site, and about 150–250 adenosines are added to the 3′ end of the RNA as a poly(A) tail.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] If this site is altered, cleavage and polyadenylation can shift to a downstream poly(A) site, producing an abnormally long and unstable mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Another difference between eukaryotes and prokaryotes is mRNA transport.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Because eukaryotic transcription and translation is compartmentally separated, eukaryotic mRNAs must be exported from the nucleus to the cytoplasm—a process that may be regulated by different signaling pathways.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Mature mRNAs are recognized by their processed modifications and then exported through the nuclear pore by binding to the cap-binding proteins CBP20 and CBP80, as well as the transcription/export complex (TREX).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Multiple mRNA export pathways have been identified in eukaryotes.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In spatially complex cells, some mRNAs are transported to particular subcellular destinations.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In mature neurons, certain mRNA are transported from the soma to dendrites.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] One site of mRNA translation is at polyribosomes selectively localized beneath synapses.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The mRNA for Arc/Arg3.1 is induced by synaptic activity and localizes selectively near active synapses based on signals generated by NMDA receptors.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Other mRNAs also move into dendrites in response to external stimuli, such as β-actin mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] For export from the nucleus, actin mRNA associates with ZBP1 and later with 40S subunit.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The complex is bound by a motor protein and is transported to the target location (neurite extension) along the cytoskeleton.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Eventually ZBP1 is phosphorylated by Src in order for translation to be initiated.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In developing neurons, mRNAs are also transported into growing axons and especially growth cones.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Many mRNAs are marked with so-called "zip codes", which target their transport to a specific location. mRNAs can also transfer between mammalian cells through structures called tunneling nanotubes.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Because prokaryotic mRNA does not need to be processed or transported, translation by the ribosome can begin immediately after the end of transcription.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Therefore, it can be said that prokaryotic translation is *coupled* to transcription and occurs *co-transcriptionally*.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In eukaryotic cells the process of translation starts with the information stored in the nucleotide sequence of DNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This is first transformed into mRNA, then transfer RNA (tRNA) specifies which three-nucleotide codon from the genetic code corresponds to which amino acid.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Eukaryotic mRNA that has been processed and transported to the cytoplasm (i.e., mature mRNA) can then be translated by ribosomes.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Translation may occur at ribosomes free in the cytoplasm, or targeted to the endoplasmic reticulum by the signal recognition particle.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Therefore, unlike in prokaryotes, eukaryotic translation is not directly coupled to transcription.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In some contexts, protein abundance can increase even when mRNA abundance decreases, because translation efficiency and protein turnover are regulated independently of transcript levels; this has been reported for mRNA and protein levels of EEF1A1 in breast cancer.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Coding regions are composed of codons, which are decoded and translated into proteins by the ribosome; in eukaryotes usually into one and in prokaryotes usually into several.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Coding regions begin with the start codon and end with a stop codon.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In general, the start codon is an AUG triplet and the stop codon is UAG ("amber"), UAA ("ochre"), or UGA ("opal").
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The coding regions tend to be stabilized by internal base pairs; this impedes degradation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In addition to being protein-coding, portions of coding regions may serve as regulatory sequences in the pre-mRNA as exonic splicing enhancers or exonic splicing silencers.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Untranslated regions (UTRs) are sections of the mRNA before the start codon and after the stop codon that are not translated, termed the five prime untranslated region (5' UTR) and three prime untranslated region (3' UTR), respectively.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] These regions are transcribed with the coding region and thus are exonic as they are present in the mature mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Several roles in gene expression have been attributed to the untranslated regions, including mRNA stability, mRNA localization, and translational efficiency.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The ability of a UTR to perform these functions depends on the sequence of the UTR and can differ between mRNAs.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Genetic variants in 3' UTR have also been implicated in disease susceptibility because of the change in RNA structure and protein translation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The stability of mRNAs may be controlled by the 5' UTR and/or 3' UTR due to varying affinity for RNA degrading enzymes called ribonucleases and for ancillary proteins that can promote or inhibit RNA degradation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Translational efficiency, including sometimes the complete inhibition of translation, can be controlled by UTRs.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Proteins that bind to either the 3' or 5' UTR may affect translation by influencing the ribosome's ability to bind to the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] MicroRNAs bound to the 3' UTR also may affect translational efficiency or mRNA stability.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Cytoplasmic localization of mRNA is thought to be a function of the 3' UTR.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Proteins that are needed in a particular region of the cell can also be translated there; in such a case, the 3' UTR may contain sequences that allow the transcript to be localized to this region for translation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Some of the elements contained in untranslated regions form a characteristic secondary structure when transcribed into RNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] These structural mRNA elements are involved in regulating the mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Some, such as the SECIS element, are targets for proteins to bind.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] One class of mRNA element, the riboswitches, directly bind small molecules, changing their fold to modify levels of transcription or translation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In these cases, the mRNA regulates itself.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The 3' poly(A) tail is a long sequence of adenine nucleotides (often several hundred) added to the 3' end of the pre-mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This tail promotes export from the nucleus and translation, and protects the mRNA from degradation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] An mRNA molecule is said to be monocistronic when it contains the genetic information to translate only a single protein chain (polypeptide).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This is the case for most of the eukaryotic mRNAs.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] On the other hand, polycistronic mRNA carries several open reading frames (ORFs), each of which is translated into a polypeptide.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] These polypeptides usually have a related function (they often are the subunits composing a final complex protein) and their coding sequence is grouped and regulated together in a regulatory region, containing a promoter and an operator.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Most of the mRNA found in bacteria and archaea is polycistronic, as is the human mitochondrial genome.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Dicistronic or bicistronic mRNA encodes only two proteins.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In eukaryotes mRNA molecules form circular structures due to an interaction between the eIF4E and poly(A)-binding protein, which both bind to eIF4G, forming an mRNA-protein-mRNA bridge.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Circularization is thought to promote cycling of ribosomes on the mRNA leading to time-efficient translation, and may also function to ensure only intact mRNA are translated (partially degraded mRNA characteristically have no m7G cap, or no poly-A tail).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Other mechanisms for circularization exist, particularly in viruses.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In several RNA viruses, long-distance RNA interactions and/or protein-mediated bridges between the 5' and 3' ends can promote translation and genome replication.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] RNA virus genomes (the + strands of which are translated as mRNA) are also commonly circularized.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Different mRNAs within the same cell have distinct lifetimes (stabilities).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In bacterial cells, individual mRNAs can survive from seconds to more than an hour.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] However, the lifetime averages between 1 and 3 minutes, making bacterial mRNA much less stable than eukaryotic mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In mammalian cells, mRNA lifetimes range from several minutes to days.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The greater the stability of an mRNA the more protein may be produced from that mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The limited lifetime of mRNA enables a cell to alter protein synthesis rapidly in response to its changing needs.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] There are many mechanisms that lead to the destruction of an mRNA, some of which are described below.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In general, in prokaryotes the lifetime of mRNA is much shorter than in eukaryotes.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Prokaryotes degrade messages by using a combination of ribonucleases, including endonucleases, 3' exonucleases, and 5' exonucleases.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In some instances, small RNA molecules (sRNA) tens to hundreds of nucleotides long can stimulate the degradation of specific mRNAs by base-pairing with complementary sequences and facilitating ribonuclease cleavage by RNase III.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] It was recently shown that bacteria also have a sort of 5' cap consisting of a triphosphate on the 5' end.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Removal of two of the phosphates leaves a 5' monophosphate, causing the message to be destroyed by the exonuclease RNase J, which degrades 5' to 3'.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Inside eukaryotic cells, there is a balance between the processes of translation and mRNA decay.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Messages that are being actively translated are typically associated with cap-binding and translation initiation factors and with poly(A)-binding protein, which can antagonize deadenylation and decapping and help protect mRNA ends from decay machinery.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The balance between translation and decay is reflected in the size and abundance of cytoplasmic structures known as P-bodies.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The poly(A) tail of the mRNA is shortened by specialized exonucleases that are targeted to specific messenger RNAs by a combination of cis-regulatory sequences on the RNA and trans-acting RNA-binding proteins.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Poly(A) tail removal is thought to disrupt the circular structure of the message and destabilize the cap binding complex.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The message is then subject to degradation by either the exosome complex or the decapping complex.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In this way, translationally inactive messages can be destroyed quickly, while active messages remain intact.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The mechanism by which translation stops and the message is handed-off to decay complexes is not understood in detail.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The majority of mRNA decay was believed to be cytoplasmic; however, recently, a novel mRNA decay pathway was described, which starts in the nucleus.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The presence of AU-rich elements in some mammalian mRNAs tends to destabilize those transcripts through the action of cellular proteins that bind these sequences and stimulate poly(A) tail removal.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Loss of the poly(A) tail is thought to promote mRNA degradation by facilitating attack by both the exosome complex and the decapping complex.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Rapid mRNA degradation via AU-rich elements is a critical mechanism for preventing the overproduction of potent cytokines such as tumor necrosis factor (TNF) and granulocyte-macrophage colony stimulating factor (GM-CSF).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] AU-rich elements also regulate the biosynthesis of proto-oncogenic transcription factors like c-Jun and c-Fos.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Eukaryotic messages are subject to surveillance by nonsense-mediated decay (NMD), which checks for the presence of premature stop codons (nonsense codons) in the message.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] These can arise via incomplete splicing, V(D)J recombination in the adaptive immune system, mutations in DNA, transcription errors, leaky scanning by the ribosome causing a frame shift, and other causes.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Detection of a premature stop codon triggers mRNA degradation by 5' decapping, 3' poly(A) tail removal, or endonucleolytic cleavage.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In metazoans, small interfering RNAs (siRNAs) processed by Dicer are incorporated into a complex known as the RNA-induced silencing complex or RISC.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] This complex contains an endonuclease that cleaves perfectly complementary messages to which the siRNA binds.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The resulting mRNA fragments are then destroyed by exonucleases. siRNA is commonly used in laboratories to block the function of genes in cell culture.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] It is thought to be part of the innate immune system as a defense against double-stranded RNA viruses.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] MicroRNAs (miRNAs) are small RNAs that typically are partially complementary to sequences in metazoan messenger RNAs.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Binding of a miRNA to a message can repress translation of that message and accelerate poly(A) tail removal, thereby hastening mRNA degradation.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The mechanism of action of miRNAs is the subject of active research.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] There are other ways by which messages can be degraded, including non-stop decay and silencing by Piwi-interacting RNA (piRNA), among others.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The administration of a nucleoside-modified messenger RNA sequence can cause a cell to make a protein, which in turn could directly treat a disease or could function as a vaccine; more indirectly the protein could drive an endogenous stem cell to differentiate in a desired way.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The primary challenges of RNA therapy center on delivering the RNA to the appropriate cells.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Challenges include the fact that naked RNA sequences naturally degrade after preparation; they may trigger the body's immune system to attack them as an invader; and they are impermeable to the cell membrane.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Once within the cell, they must then leave the cell's transport mechanism to take action within the cytoplasm, which houses the necessary ribosomes.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Gene editing therapies such as CRISPR may also benefit from using mRNA to induce cells to make the desired Cas protein.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Since the 2010s, RNA vaccines and other RNA therapeutics have been considered to be "a new class of drugs".
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The first mRNA-based vaccines received restricted authorization and were rolled out across the world during the COVID-19 pandemic by Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine and Moderna, for example.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] The 2023 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded to Katalin Karikó and Drew Weissman for the development of effective mRNA vaccines against COVID-19.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] New approaches to modulate RNA levels as a therapeutics include the use of antisense oligonucleotides, including for neurodevelopment diseases associated with high mortality.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Several molecular biology studies during the early 1950s suggested that RNA played a role in protein synthesis, though the specific role remained unclear.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] For example, in one of the earliest reports, Ayaka Stephanie Hogg and his team showed that RNA synthesis was necessary for protein synthesis, specifically during the production of the enzyme β-galactosidase in the bacterium *E. coli*.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Arthur Pardee also found similar RNA accumulation in 1954.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In 1953, Alfred Hershey, June Dixon, and Martha Chase studied *E. coli* infected with bacteriophage T2 and reported that the bacterium's own DNA decreased while the phage's DNA built up inside the infected cells (including DNA containing 5-hydroxymethylcytosine).
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In hindsight, this has been discussed as part of the chain of observations that led to the concept of mRNA, and it was not recognized at the time as such.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] With Crick's encouragement, Brenner and Jacob immediately set out to test this new hypothesis, and they contacted Matthew Meselson at the California Institute of Technology for assistance.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] During the summer of 1960, Brenner, Jacob, and Meselson conducted an experiment in Meselson's laboratory at Caltech which was the first to prove the existence of mRNA.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] That fall, Jacob and Monod coined the name "messenger RNA" and developed the first theoretical framework to explain its function.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] In February 1961, James Watson revealed that his Harvard-based research group had been right behind them with a series of experiments whose results pointed in roughly the same direction.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] Brenner and the others agreed to Watson's request to delay publication of their research findings.
[src:messenger-rna/messenger-rna] As a result, the Brenner and Watson articles were published simultaneously in the same issue of *Nature* in May 1961, while that same month, Jacob and Monod published their theoretical framework for mRNA in the *Journal of Molecular Biology*.
